NATIVE VLAN
==============

Native VLAN Encapsulation:
- ISL 
- 802.1Q

Behavior:
ISL - Encapsulates "all" frames sent out ISL Trunks. 
Cisco proprietary 802.1Q - Native VLAN - 802.1Q add vlan header to all frames sent out 
except for frames originating from its native vlan

- Frames from the native VLAN, by default are sent out on 802.1q trunks untagged
- If receiving 802.1q trunk receives an untagged frames, it will automatically assign that incoming frame to its native vlan.
- it is required that both end to end trunks must have the same native vlans configured.

- Native VLAN by default: VLAN 1 = untagged packet forwarded to vlan 1
- By default, all frames from VLAN 1 will be sent out untagged on 802.1q trunks
- End to end trunk links must have the same native vlan configured

NOTE:
- The native VLAN by default is the default VLAN1
- the Default VLAN is NOT The Native VLAN
- The Native VLAN can be changed to be a different VLAN

- The default Native VLAN is always VLAN1
- The Native VLAN can be changed to be a different VLAN
- Trunks links can have different native vlans per link but, 
a point-to-point trunk link must have the same native vlan.


- Syntax: 
conf t
int f0/1
switchport trunk encapsulation dot1q
switchport mode trunk 
switchport trunk native vlan <vlan id>
exit



